				<outline text="For 40 Years, Crashing Trains Was One of Americaâs Favorite Pastimes. https://t.co/VaocEQxRFa" type="tweet" created="Sat, 12 Jun 2021 15:17:13 GMT" tweetId="1403733134122930176" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1403733134122930176" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
				<outline text="My Android phone, a Pixel 4a, goes offline all the damn time. I have to restart it to get it back online." type="tweet" created="Sat, 12 Jun 2021 14:54:23 GMT" tweetId="1403727385535655937" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1403727385535655937" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
				<outline text="If you want to blog from an outliner, I suggest the first step is to get the outline data to flow out of your editing tool in OPML, and then write your publishing software to build the blog from the OPML. That way you won't be locked into your editor or publishing software." type="tweet" created="Sat, 12 Jun 2021 14:32:43 GMT" tweetId="1403721933628350474" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1403721933628350474" inReplyToId="" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
					<outline text="There are lots of approaches to both writing and publishing. You won't get the benefit if you don't have a strong basis for interop. 

Silos have a long history of being bad for progress." type="tweet" created="Sat, 12 Jun 2021 14:32:43 GMT" tweetId="1403721934433554440" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1403721934433554440" inReplyToId="1403721933628350474" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
						<outline text="PS: For most of the last 26 years I've been writing my blog in an outliner. I'm glad that other people are interested in this now. Let's build a new community around this idea. ;-)" type="tweet" created="Sat, 12 Jun 2021 14:32:43 GMT" tweetId="1403721935373144069" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1403721935373144069" inReplyToId="1403721934433554440" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
